utterances.utterance: That is not how you feed fish.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- [unintelligible] how do you know all of this?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I knew that because CNN deceptively edited that video, and that was one of those fake news items that we like to talk about.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Ah. Good memory.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: There was a parade in New York City this week for the U.S. women's soccer team. It was interrupted by a presidential candidate trying to steal the spotlight for himself, greedily. He even led the crowd in an awkward chant. Which presidential candidate did this at the parade?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Hey, my buzzer.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's got to be --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Jesse Watters.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- Mayor Bill de Blasio.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I always forget he's a presidential candidate --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Doesn't everybody else?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- in addition to being, of course, your mayor. Was it Bill de Blasio the nation's worst mayor?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BILL DE BLASIO
utterances.utterance: I want to hear one more deafening roar --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BILL DE BLASIO
utterances.utterance: -- because of what they stand for. Let me hear you say it, "USA, equal pay. USA, equal pay. USA, equal pay."

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: All right.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Nancy Pelosi, speaker of the House, has given Mitch McConnell, Senate majority leader, a new nickname. It sounds unflattering, but apparently, McConnell loves it so much he put it on T-shirts. What is the new nickname? Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think it's the grim reaper.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: The grim reaper. Is it the grim reaper? That would be hilarious.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Speaker Pelosi has a new nickname for Senate majority leader, well, Mitch McConnell, the grim reaper.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: She's got it right. She's got it absolutely right. I -- for the first time in my memory, I agree with Nancy Pelosi. I am indeed the grim reaper.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He likes it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Amazing. There are over 20 Democrats running for president. They're finding all kinds of ways to get people's attention. Which candidate just released a political ad in which he changed a baby's diaper?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Eric Swalwell.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: That's too embarrassing even for actual -- I don't believe you, Jesse Watters. Let's see if it's true.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Eric Swalwell is also struggling --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Ooh.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: -- to make the debate stage so now he's bringing in his infant to help.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Yeah, that's not -- it's not actually good -- by the way, good job. It's not true that just because you can change a diaper you can run a government. I -- I happen to know. In their match against Thailand this week, the American women's soccer team won the most lopsided game in the history of the World Cup. What was the final score?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Jesse Watters.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I knew that.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is that correct? Was it really 13-0?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Tonight, the U.S. women's soccer team is on defense after that historic World Cup win against Thailand 13-0.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Quite on par with the legendary Shannon Bream, though close. Later tonight, we'll show you who put an end to his running streak. But up next, a very special edition of Final Exam in which we pit a married couple against one another in a quiz about food. Diabolical.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Welcome back to our Final Exam special. Congressman Sean Duffy and his wife, Fox contributor, Rachel Campos-Duffy, are one of Washington's most recognizable couples. They've got eight children together. But then we decided to bring them on for a special food themed edition of Final Exam. We hope their marriage is able to survive what happened next.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Is there any way I win this, Tucker? I mean, I think I --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: No, there's literally no chance. And by the way, winning doesn't actually get you a victory. That's another show entirely.

utterances.speaker: REP. SEAN DUFFY, R-WIS.
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So, according to the rules laid out by the National Game Show Commission, all of today's questions must be either about food or animals. We went with food. So, the first question -- this is multiple choice. Please listen carefully. President Trump says he doesn't care what law makers call the border wall and ordered a food -- offered a food related suggestion. Which name did he suggest? Was it, A, quarter pounder with cheese, B, pancakes, C, peaches?

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY, FOX NEWS CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible]

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I think it goes, by definition, to your husband. I'm sorry. The judges have weighed in on this.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I'm going to go with C, peaches.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You're going to go with C. Is it peaches?

utterances.speaker: Donald Trump
utterances.utterance: Whatever you want to call it's okay with me. They can name it whatever. They can name it peaches. I don't care what they name it. But we need money. Peaches.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Peaches.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Peaches. You both you knew that.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I did and I thought the question was over. My mistake.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You knew it too well, I think that's what it was.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I did.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: So, she has to wait for -- we -- all multiple choice have to be --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You have to wait until we finished asking the question, okay?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: We can do it this time, I know. Costco, the store, says it is sold out of a 27 tub of food that has a shelf life of 20 years. What type of food was it?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Ah, that was not -- that's not --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Rachel.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I hit it first.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: It was macaroni and cheese.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Macaroni -- I think you have to hold it down.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Oh, okay. I hit it first, for sure.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It was macaroni and cheese. Is it macaroni and cheese?

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: [audio clip] Everybody loves macaroni and cheese.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: How'd she know that?

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: [audio clip] But now you can get 27 pounds of it --

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: That's my voice, that's how I knew it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: That's not fair.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You obviously need to invest in that.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Yes. [laughs]

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Because that seems like a pretty good deal. I'm getting one myself.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I'm kind of a prepper, so I was like, I'll do it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Remember, your official position on prepping is, “Oh, that's crazy.”

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Question three. Another multiple choice, okay?

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: A world record was set this week for the most liked Instagram photo ever. The picture doesn't feature a famous person or an exotic place. It has already nearly 50 million likes. It's a plain, boring, photograph of what? A, a banana, B, a lemon, C, an egg. Congressman?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I'm going to go with Kylie Jenner, I believe, and C, an egg. Didn't she tweet the egg out?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I have no idea.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Let's check it out.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: But I'm not a member of Congress. Is it C, the egg?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: “World Record Egg.” An account with that very name posted this single photo. It's a picture of an egg. The egg currently has 26 million likes and counting.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: How did that--

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You know, you live in this country your whole life and you still don't understand it. What is that?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: There must be, like, an egg commission that promotes eggs. And they're getting a bonus. They're getting a bonus on this one.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: The poultry lobby is behind it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Question four. One last multiple choice.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It's chaos.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I'm winning, though, right? It's two to one.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I'm not going to -- it's not for me to keep score. Our viewers are watching. Chaos hit Flagstaff, Arizona on Monday when a tanker truck flipped over spilling 3,500 gallons of which liquid all over the highway. Was it, A, chocolate, B, coffee, C, beer. Rachel.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Beer. C.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Was it C --

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I don't know.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- beer?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I don't know.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: 3,500 gallons, that's how much liquid chocolate spilled in an Arizona -- -- interstate. A chocolate river, they described it forming after a tanker --

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I thought it was weird, too.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I just took a guess. [laughs]

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You don't [inaudible]

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I was losing and I figured beer. Why would chocolate be on a truck?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You know what, you doubled down and I -- you know, I admire that.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: She's from Wisconsin, so of course she said beer.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I love beer. [laughs]

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Of course, she said beer. Cheese not being liquid.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: All right, final question. The Clemson Tigers invited to the White House for a candlelit feast to celebrate their recent victory over Alabama. What type of food did the president serve the team? Congressman Duffy.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I was there this morning -- McDonald's. From the McDonald's that the food came from, I was there this morning.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Was it McDonald's?

utterances.speaker: Donald Trump
utterances.utterance: We have pizzas, we have 300 hamburgers, many, many French fries. All of our favorite foods. I want to see what's here when we leave. Because I don't think it's going to be much.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: And Carlos owns the store.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: And it wasn't -- I just want to say, it wasn't exclusively, we're hearing from our judges --

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: It's fast --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- McDonald's. But, McDonald's was represented.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So, in our -- and you're right. You still win, because McDonald's -- it was McDonald's, Wendy's, and what was the last one?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I was going to say fast food.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Burger King. So, it was an ecumenical --

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Carlos owns the McDonald's; they gave the food to the White House --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So impressive. Congressman -- well --

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: He's had -- like, there's been a shut down. He's had a lot of time.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Exactly, but I would also say --

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: I've been home with the kids.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It's a shared victory. It's really a victory for your family. We're pro-family on this show. So, I'm going to reward, in fact, our Erik Wemple commemorative mug to you, Rachel.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Thank you, Tucker. I'm truly honored.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: That was great. Congratulations to you both.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Can I tell you -- I went and watched the episode that you had with him on, it's great. YouTube it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It really -- when I'm feeling sad, sometimes I pull it up and it just kind of lifts me a little.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Or, if you're on a shut down --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Exactly, that's right.

utterances.speaker: RACHEL CAMPOS-DUFFY
utterances.utterance: -- pull up a YouTube video.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: The National Game Show Commission, located in lovely downtown Billings, Montana, has demanded a roundup of our best animal related Final Exam questions, and of course we had to oblige. That's next, as our special continues.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Welcome back to our Final Exam special. Mark Steyn, you know if you watch this show, probably our favorite guest here on the program. He's also an excellent guest host and a brilliant writer. But how did he perform when put to the test on final exam? He competed against Pete Hegseth to answer questions about everything from record-setting jeopardy contestants to exotic birds blocking runways. Here's what happened.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Question one is a multiple choice. You have to wait to hear the options. Here it is: Scientists have moved beyond creating useful robots. They're now building machines that do completely useless things. A robot unveiled in -- no surprise -- Japan has been trained to do something related to sports. Is it A, hit a half-court shot; B, ice skate; or C, throw a curve ball?

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH, FOX NEWS
utterances.utterance: Oh, I thought I had it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Mark Steyn.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible] ice skate.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is it ice skate? Has the robot been trained to ice skate?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Two, three.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: You know, whether you're Canadian biased. [Laughter]

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: It's not curling.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Nope.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: That is the old James Name Smith [spelled phonetically].

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It's the old -- the traditional Japanese sport of basketball. Well, question two, this one another multiple choice. This week on the other celebrity quiz show, Jeopardy, a contestant set a record for the most money won on a single episode. How much did he win? Was it A, $90,000; B, $100,000, or C, 110 grand?

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: I have a faulty buzzer.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Pete Hegseth –

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: I'll take it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- we're going to give it to you.

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: Oh, I've got to press a -- oh. I'm being dainty here. I'm going to go with C, 110,000 bucks.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: 110,000. Is Pete Hegseth correct?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Congratulations are in order to a Jeopardy contestant who won a record amount of money on yesterday's show. Watch.

utterances.speaker: ALEX TREBEK
utterances.utterance: And a new one-day record, 110,000 --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: He wins another $400,000. He can bribe his kids into USC.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: That's true.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Good lie. That's true.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Power of a good guess.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: All right. You've been watching game shows to practice. Smart. Okay, yet another multiple choice question.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: This is about a plane in Spain that could not take off in the rain, also something -- it's like dog roll. Passengers were stuck on the tarmac because a bird was strutting down the runway. What type of bird was it? Was it, A, a pigeon; B, a crane; or C, a flamingo? Mark Steyn.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: I've got to go with a crane in Spain.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Woof! Was it a crane in Spain next to the plane?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I don't think they have cranes.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Despite honking horns and impatient pilots, it took its sweet time strutting down the tarmac. Airport crew tried to scare it off. And at one point, it did fly away, but then it flew back in a matter of seconds. Flamingo finally left –

utterances.speaker: All
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: -- from the wildlife, including the [unintelligible].

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible] by the animal.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Flamingo. This goes to my theory there's an inverse relationship between IQ and performance on this show.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: I was thinking too laterally. I didn't -- I should have gone with flamingo.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Okay. The old bun got you.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: I thought I [unintelligible].

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: But it was good. It was -- it was worth losing. All right. This is our -- today's daily double. It's a two-point question per our judges. Question four: Some fans of Bernie Sanders are angry at him this week because he confessed to something they considered controversial. What did he confess to?

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: Being --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Pete Hegseth.

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: -- a million -- being a millionaire.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Being a millionaire.

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is that -- is that right?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Senator Bernie Sanders says he is a millionaire. The Vermont senator has denounced millionaires for years.

utterances.speaker: Bernie Sanders
utterances.utterance: I wrote two books in recent years. One of them was a best seller on the New York Times best-seller list, translated to five or six languages --

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: Bernie Sanders
utterances.utterance: It did very well. I made money on that book.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Capitalism, great for him.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible].

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Great for him. Did he put his pinkie to his mouth when he said, "Millionaire?"

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Yeah, what languages did Bernie's book get translated into? I cannot --

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: One language: Green, Mark. Green.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Estonian, that was it. All right, final question, also a multiple choice. Here we go. Astronomers have captured the first ever image of a black hole. Some say it looks like a doughnut, others say it looks like a dragon's eye. How far away is this from earth? Is it, A, 2 million light years away; B, 50 million light years away; or C, 100 million light years away? Mark Steyn.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: I am going to go with 2 million light years away.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: 2 million. Twice as far as Bernie is rich; is that correct?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible] the most famous doughnut hole of all time. That first image of a black hole.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I never believed that this black hole was as big as people said until we saw that.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Ebb 87 is over 50 million light years away.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: Oh, [unintelligible].

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You took the risk.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: No, well, they -- the black hole of my career after this performance is actually --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You didn't only lose, Mark Steyn, you lost spectacularly, floridly. You're en fuego in your loss. And congratulations to you for doing so so memorably. Pete Hegseth.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You win a coveted Wemple mug.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible] put in an Eric Wemple mug from Jeff Bezos' website.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: For Jeff Bezos's website, in the mail, may you treasure it, may you fill it with bourbon.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: I don't mind losing to Lisa Boothe? I'm going to lose, and this man cried at Titanic.

utterances.speaker: Pete Hegesth
utterances.utterance: I do.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: He's girlier than List Boothe.

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: Every time the Titanic plays, I cry. It's so good. It's true.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It's going to be weeks before I can digest this segment. Thank you, gentleman, both of you.

utterances.speaker: MARK STEYN
utterances.utterance: Thanks, Tucker.

utterances.speaker: PETE HEGSETH
utterances.utterance: Thank you, Tucker.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: We interrupt this program with a special request by the National Game Show Commission of Billings, Montana. Not even a request, really, a demand. They would like a selection of our best animal themed questioned on Final Exam. We would never think of defying the National Game Show Commission. So, we're going to go ahead and give them to you. Let you know that our animal questions are pretty great, actually. Here are our best ones.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: By order of the National Game Show Commission, located in Billings, Montana, we must begin this quiz with an animal question. And it is this. The most expensive bird ever sold at auction was purchased this week for an amazing $1.4 million. What kind of bird was it?

utterances.speaker: GILLIAN TURNER, FOX NEWS
utterances.utterance: How do you know that?

utterances.speaker: LAUREN BLANCHARD, FOX NEWS
utterances.utterance: It's Armando, the pigeon.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You know his name?

utterances.speaker: BLANCHARD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, it's Armando.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It's an Armando, the pigeon.

utterances.speaker: TURNER
utterances.utterance: One person knows that in this country and it is Lauren, sitting in this room right now. Let's see if she's right.

utterances.speaker: BLANCHARD
utterances.utterance: I didn't know pigeons -- did you know pigeons were actually, like, they're very expensive?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: -- story, a European racing pigeon was recently sold for a world record $1.4 million. Before this story, I would have believed you if you said the world record price for a pigeon was $6.

utterances.speaker: TURNER
utterances.utterance: You know, I'm kicking myself, because I did scroll -- I passed that story on Twitter.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You know, it's funny, it's not the -- I have the answers on my cards, and Armando's not even on here. So, in fact, I didn't mention him either, so we're just going to assume.

utterances.speaker: TURNER
utterances.utterance: Okay.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Amazing. A central Pennsylvania man is getting global attention thanks to his strange attachment to an animal. That emotional support animal weighs 60 pounds, is five feet long, and is called Wally. What kind of animal is this? Lauren Banchard.

utterances.speaker: BLANCHARD
utterances.utterance: It's an emotional support alligator.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You don't believe it?

utterances.speaker: LAWRENCE JONES
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: BLANCHARD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Let's see it. I know, that's my reaction, Lawrence Jones. “What?”

utterances.speaker: BLANCHARD
utterances.utterance: My friend got to meet it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is it an alligator?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Wally is my emotional support alligator for my home use.

utterances.speaker: LAWRENCE JONES
utterances.utterance: Oh my God.

utterances.speaker: BLANCHARD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: But we are invited everywhere. I do take him to Lowe's and Home Depot, and he's usually always welcome there.

utterances.speaker: LAWRENCE JONES
utterances.utterance: This is getting out of hand.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I love how you phrase that. “It's my support alligator for my home use.” Norwegian fishermen believe they have discovered an actual Russian spy in their waters. This time, it's an animal, though, with a recording device attached to it's body. What kind of animal is it? Gillian.

utterances.speaker: TURNER
utterances.utterance: A whale.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: A whale? A whale. A whale can't be a spy.

utterances.speaker: TURNER
utterances.utterance: It's -- I'm telling you, it's a whale.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is it some kind of whale?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Fishermen discovering a beluga whale wearing a Russian made harness. On it were written the words, “equipment St. Petersburg,” fueling all kinds of speculation about spying. One newspaper reporting --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So, you're saying that even the whales are now spying for the Russians?

utterances.speaker: TURNER
utterances.utterance: I'm sorry, did you say you wanted to concede now?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: A popular video on the internet shows a farm animal in Ireland singing like a human. What kind of animal was it? A, a goat, B, a chicken, C, a donkey. Ed Henry.

utterances.speaker: Ed Henry
utterances.utterance: C, a donkey.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: [whistles] That's one of those questions you either know it or you don't. Does he know it?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Finally, we have a musical donkey. Yes, you heard it right here, folks.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: How did you know that?

utterances.speaker: Ed Henry
utterances.utterance: I saw this. I was home.

utterances.speaker: Ed Henry
utterances.utterance: I was off on Monday and Tuesday.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It turns out that was your strength. You said it was your weakness.

utterances.speaker: Ed Henry
utterances.utterance: I have another idea too, but I'm not going to tell you.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Frontier Airlines, the airline of the west, kicked off an Orlando woman from one of its flights this week after she boarded the plan with a prohibited animal. This is multiple choice. What kind of animal was it? Was it, A, a python --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: No, no.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Kristin Fisher. Kristin loses a point that goes to Bret.

utterances.speaker: Kristin Fisher
utterances.utterance: Just like that?

utterances.speaker: Bret Baier
utterances.utterance: Oh, dear. I could get the right answer, so I get another point?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You tie it up, in which case, we need a tie breaker.

utterances.speaker: Kristin Fisher
utterances.utterance: -- horribly unfair.

utterances.speaker: Bret Baier
utterances.utterance: That's right.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: They're unfair, but those are the rules. It's like the electoral college. It's in the constitution, Kristin Fisher. We can't change it. Okay.

utterances.speaker: Bret Baier
utterances.utterance: Here it is.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So, Brett. Did she refuse to fly without A, a python, B, a squirrel, or C, a raccoon.

utterances.speaker: Bret Baier
utterances.utterance: A squirrel.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Was it B, a squirrel?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: A woman was kicked off a flight after bringing an emotional support squirrel onto the plane. Frontier Airlines only allows dogs or cats.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I said, it's multiple choice and you knew the answer-- The craziest video of this week shows an angry animal chasing a group of snowboarder down a mountain in Colorado. What kind of animal was it? Was it A, a mouse, B, a mountain lion, C, a black bear. Congressman Duffy.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: It would be mouse, Tucker.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: A mouse?

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I would have guessed mountain lion.

utterances.speaker: SEAN DUFFY
utterances.utterance: Mouse.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is it a mouse?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: A mouse is on the loose and charges at skiers and snowboarders. Look at this video. Wild video showing the giant animal chasing the group in Aspen, Colorado. They say it followed them for half a mile.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Question: police in Houston, Texas received an unusual call this week from a man they thought was hallucinating. The man called to tell them he had entered an abandoned home to smoke marijuana and found what kind of wild jungle cat inside the house? Lauren Blanchard.

utterances.speaker: Lauren Blanchard
utterances.utterance: It was a caged tiger.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Come on, now.

utterances.speaker: Lauren Blanchard
utterances.utterance: It was.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Was it a tiger?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Two Houston men snuck into an abandoned house to smoke some reefer and they wound up seeing a tiger inside. Luckily for them, they got out of there before the crouching tiger caught a contact high from their hidden bong and got the munchies.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You even knew it was caged. If you're in New York City, researchers are about to begin work on a new census. This time they are not counting people, however. They're focusing on a small furry creature in Central Park. What kind of animal is it?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: No, are they counting? I was waiting.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: She's reading a teleprompter.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: You've got to read the script.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: She's reading the teleprompter.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You know you're not allowed to read the teleprompter.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Wait a second. I'm going back to something I said earlier, which is, when you have cable news anchors on your show --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Wait a minute, he did finish the question.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- things fall apart.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Okay, let me just check with the judges really quick.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: No, you didn't. Huh?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: The judges say the host of the program is allowed to ab-lib on his own script, so I think that's --

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: She's reading it.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: What is the answer?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I'm going to say squirrels.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: It is squirrels.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: It is squirrels. You know it, but you answered it -- why would it not be rats? Is it squirrels?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: New York City is about to conduct its first official squirrel census next week. Volunteers are needed.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: This is literally the most contentious show we've ever had.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Yeah. But I won.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So, what happens when two of the very smartest people at Fox HQ in New York City face off with questions about the most hated Mayor in the United States? It's Kennedy versus Janice Dean on our Final Exam special, next.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Got an awful lot of sharp people here at Fox News as you know. And sometimes we can get them to match witnesses on Final Exam. On one recent show we brought together two of the top mines at our Fox News New York headquarters. Fox Business host Kennedy and Fox meteorologist Janice Dean. Talks included the demise of Grumpy Cat and a great white shark headed straight for New York City. Here's what happened next.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Okay, question one. This is multiple choice. Grumpy Cat, who was exactly what it sounds like, frowny-faced feline, had her own Lifetime movie, died at the age of seven. At one point, she was reputed to be worth a hundred million dollars. Not clear how that works, but that's what they said. What was Grumpy Cat's real name? Was it, A, Gizmo; B, Tartar Sauce; C, Cabbage Patch?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I have no idea.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I'm not risking it.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Me neither. Has this ever happened --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Not risking it.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: -- where no one answers?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Nope, not going to lose a point.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You know, it's never happened before.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: But we're going to just -- we're going to --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: What do we do?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I was listening for the judge's instructions.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Do we dance?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: We're going to give you --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Think I'm going to dance now. Oh!

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: We're going to give you one hint, 'kay? And the first one to buzz in. Here's the hint. It's like a condiment.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh!

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Kennedy.

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Tartar Sauce.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Wow.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You're not going to go with Gizmo? Okay. Tartar Sauce.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Ah, the hint.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Heaven got a little grumpy yes, sir. Tartar Sauce, known globally as Grumpy Cat, passed away this week peacefully in the arms of her Mommy. At one point, it was estimated the famous feline was worth a hundred million dollars.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: More than we are [unintelligible].

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: [unintelligible] very good.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Apparent -- according to our judges, we can't let a question go unanswered.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Okay. Well, this is a first, Tucker.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I'm not quite sure why.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I mean, this is the exciting if this is a first.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: These are the rules. I don't know.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Girls rule, boys drool.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I don't make the rules. I just -- I carry them out. All right, question two. According to a new poll from Quinnipiac, Joe Biden is the most liked Democrat in the presidential field. The most disliked candidate has an unfavorable rating of 45 percent. Who is that?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Ugh!

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Kennedy.

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Bill de Blasio.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Bill -- you're just saying that because you live in New York. Is it Bill de Blasio?

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: I bet you it is.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Mayor Bill de Blasio, he's finally ahead in one category. He is the winner in the most disliked candidate running for president. According to the Quinnipiac poll, 45 percent dislike Bill de Blasio.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Who is now in heaven with Tartar Sauce, the ground hog.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: That's true. Grumpy the Cat and Tartar Sauce.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: He's in heaven with Tartar Sauce.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: The ground hog, remember Staten Island [unintelligible].

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I get -- I get that joke. We played that video the other night. It's too good.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: It's fun.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Ooh.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: All right, question three. Question three is our daily double. It's a two-point question, and it's also multiple choice.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Ooh.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Here we go. In an interview this week, Democratic candidate Kamala Harris said her ideal running mate in 2020 would be which historical figure? Was it A, Mahatma Ghandi; B, Susan B. Anthony, or C, Cashious Clay, aka Mohammad Ali?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I don't know.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Kennedy.

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: I -- you know, I could be throwing all this away because this would be my idea. I would say Cassius Clay. Mama call it Clay, I call him Clay.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is it Mohammad Ali?

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: If you could have anyone living or dead as your perfect running mate, who would it be?

utterances.speaker: Kamala Harris
utterances.utterance: Oh, Mohammad Ali.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Mohammad Ali. Oh.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: How do you like that?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I'm sorry, Tucker, she wiped the floor.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Sting like a bee, speaking of. All right. It's impressive --

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Kennedy!

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- but it's not too late.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: It's not too late?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Not too late, Janice Dean.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: All right. Can I -- can we do a dance off?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: So loved -- universally beloved Janice Dean. All right, question four: Your days of being stuck in an LA traffic jam with nothing to do are over. There is now a fast food chain that will send a motorcycle courier through the gridlock and bring a burger right to your car. Which chain is it? Janice Dean.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Burger King.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Burger King. Not In-n-Out, but burger -- is it Burger King?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I wish it was In-n-Out.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: It's a real problem. It is a real thing. And yes, Burger King wants to solve this problem.

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh!

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Once you place your order, you'll get updates. And then through a motorcycle courier, your burger, your whatever else you want to order from Burger King, that will be delivered to you.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Aha!

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: But are you that hungry in traffic that you need to eat inside your car?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: On the 405, 4:00 on a Friday, yeah.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Outstanding.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh, I'm still standing.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Okay. So this last question -- I'm just hearing this now from my judges. And as you know, this is the way the game works, they make up rules as we go along.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Amazing.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: No rhyme and no reason, but we must --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I'm all for it as a libertarian.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: -- obey.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Can we have a cocktail?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: They're like the federal government that way, and they're telling me that this final question is a three-pointer. It's also a multiple choice, okay?

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Okay. The pressure's on!

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Here we go. Some people in the northeast are very excited because a 10-foot great white shark is heading their way. It was seen last year near Greenwich, Connecticut. It could be heading to Martha's Vineyard. The shark has been given a name.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: What is the name? Is it, A, Lydia; is it B, Charles; is it C, Cabot?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Kennedy?

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Tucker, we're going to need a bigger boat. It's C, Cabot.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Oh, we're going to need a bigger -- I wonder if I audience gets that reference.

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Who doesn't get that?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: I'm just old enough to get it. So good.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Dun-dun dun-dun dun-dun.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Is it -- is it -- that's very good. Is it Cabot?

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: This great white shark named Cabot has been --

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Oh, Kennedy.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: -- detected in these waters here behind me on the Long Island Sound.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: You deserve it, man.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: The great white was named by Nova Scotians after the explorer John Cabot. The shark seems to have made its way west since then.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh. I elbowed you.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: It's okay. It's all right.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: I'm so sorry.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: Injury on that Final Exam.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Cabot. Usually I could think white cheddar, but not great white shark. Kennedy, seven points. That's the highest point total in the history of Final Exam.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh, that's amazing.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Janice Dean, this does not diminish in any way your goodness as a person or our profound and undying love for you. So thank you very much.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Just -- had to love me --

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: By the way, this would have been a win-win. If Janice Dean had won this whole thing, I would have celebrated her greatness.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: It's the same. We're gonna --

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Yeah, everyone would have. But --

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.utterance: We're celebrating.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: But Cabot? That was -- that was good. So we have an Eric Wemple mug for you. It's on the way. Maybe you'll get a whole set of them.

utterances.speaker: Kennedy
utterances.utterance: Interoffice mail.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Thank you both.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Can I come back, Tucker?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Interoffice mail. We'll send it.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: Can I come back?

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: Janice Dean
utterances.utterance: I love you.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Of course, you can come back. Are you -- we showed you how Jesse Watters effortlessly destroyed countless Final Exam challengers. But someone was finally able to beat him in one of the stormiest Final Exams of all time. Who was it? I'll show you once our special continues, next.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Welcome back to our Final Exam special. As you just saw earlier this hour, Jesse Waters looked unstoppable for much of the year. We looked everywhere to find someone capable of beating him. We needed a real hurricane of a contender, if you catch our drift. Someone who could blow Waters away. And then finally, we found him. Here it is.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: This week's first contestant is the Chief Meteorologist here at Fox. Our friend, Rick Reichmuth. The question is, we've wondered this for years, how much does he know about things that are not the weather? We're about to find out as he takes on our defending champion. He is the co-host of The Five, the host of Water's World, graduate of Trinity College in Hartford Connecticut, Jesse Waters, ladies and gentleman. And he's on a winning streak right now. Dr. Segal, Kennedy, Lisa Boothe, Emily Compagno, Susan Lee, Benjamin Hall, all have been wiped out by Waters. Can Rick Reichmuth turn the tide?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, nice analogies, I love that.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: Are you ready, Rick?

utterances.speaker: Rick Reichmuth
utterances.utterance: Hopefully. Hopefully. Seven seems like too many for this guy.

utterances.speaker: CARLSON
utterances.utterance: You're very laid back. We'll see. Okay. I know you know the rules. I'm going to repeat them for the sake of our viewers. Hands on buzzers, I ask the questions, the first one to buzz in gets to answer the question. You must wait, critically, until I finish asking it before you answer. You can answer once I acknowledge you by saying your name. Every correct answer is worth a single point, each incorrect answer subtracts a point from your total. Best of five wins. Are you prepared?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, we are.
